main event: A civilian reported observing a large object and two smaller objects in Coeburn, VA in August 1959. The objects moved at a slow speed and changed colors from reddish to white then green and then white again. These objects were captured in a photograph using a 35mm camera without flash or special equipment.
interesting points: The objects changed colors and were about twice as bright as the largest star on a clear night.
The Air Force analyzed the photograph and suggested that the spots on the film were 'air bells' due to poor developing techniques.
The objects were observed rising steadily and following the top of the mountain ridge, with two of them going below the mountain at one point.
Sketches were provided by the witness, showing the path and arrangement of the objects as well as the witness's perception of their appearance.
The witness claimed that Secret Service agents checked the objects during the summer of 1959 and that Strategic Air Command (SAC) dropped strips of aluminum over the area to jam the Navy's radar.
result: The analysis of the photograph suggested that the spots on the film were likely due to poor developing techniques and were not seen as indicative of an unidentified flying object. The witness's claim regarding government involvement in the incident was not further addressed in the document.
sighted object: One large object and two smaller objects, changing colors and appearing about twice as bright as the largest star on a clear night.
